observe.prompt:
You are vowel_agent. Public information about the environment:
{environment->public_information}
Your private information:
{agents->vowel_agent->private_information}
Your role is to describe what you observe (which blocks are topmost and available to you) and to report an abstract, structured description of the actions you can perform (for example: pickup-top ?x, put-on ?x ?y, put-on-table ?x). Do not produce PDDL domain/problem files. Be explicit about which specific vowel blocks you can move in the initial state and any preconditions/effects for your abstract action templates. Output this as plain structured text that the orchestrator can consume.

You are consonant_agent. Public information about the environment:
{environment->public_information}
Your private information:
{agents->consonant_agent->private_information}
Your role is to describe what you observe (which blocks are topmost and available to you) and to report an abstract, structured description of the actions you can perform (for example: pickup-top ?x, put-on ?x ?y, put-on-table ?x). Do not produce PDDL domain/problem files. Be explicit about which specific consonant blocks you can move in the initial state and any preconditions/effects for your abstract action templates. Output this as plain structured text that the orchestrator can consume.

compose_pddl.prompt:
You are orchestrator. Public information:
{environment->public_information}
Agents' private information:
vowel_agent: {agents->vowel_agent->private_information}
consonant_agent: {agents->consonant_agent->private_information}
Here is the structured observation / abstract model reported by the vowel agent:
{info_vowel_agent}
Here is the structured observation / abstract model reported by the consonant agent:
{info_consonant_agent}
Global goal to achieve:
{agents->orchestrator->goal}
Tasks:
1) Integrate the two agents' abstract action descriptions into a single PDDL domain that enforces (a) only-top-blocks movable, (b) single-block moves, and (c) the vowel vs consonant manipulation restriction. You may represent agent-specific permissions as separate action schemas (e.g., pickup-vowel, put-vowel-on, pickup-consonant, put-consonant-on) or by adding an agent-type parameter and typing predicates, but keep action names distinct so plans can be attributed to agents.
2) Encode the initial configuration exactly as given in the public information.
3) Encode the goal: A on B, B on C, C on D, D on E, E on F, F on G, G on H, H on I, I on J, J on table.
4) Ensure the PDDL is compatible with FastDownward (include required :requirements and use STRIPS/typing appropriately). Use predicates such as (on ?x ?y), (ontable ?x), (clear ?x), and any typing needed.
Provide the final PDDL domain and PDDL problem. Enclose the domain between <domain></domain> and the problem between <problem></problem>.
